          "body": "Verses 11-13 contain one of the Old Testament's most vivid portraits of divine anger as a warrior's readiness for battle. God has 'indignation every day' (7:11) — His moral outrage against evil is not a periodic reaction but a continuous posture. And if a man does not repent, God will 'sharpen His sword,' 'bend His bow and make it ready,' prepare 'deadly weapons,' and make His 'arrows fiery shafts.' The imagery is drawn from the arsenal of an ancient Near Eastern warrior, applied to the divine King. Reformed theologians including John Owen and Jonathan Edwards were careful here: this wrath is not capricious cruelty but the holy outrage of moral perfection against moral violation. The conditional is still open in verse 12 — 'if a man does not repent.' The sharpening has begun; the shot has not yet been released. Repentance remains possible. But the window is defined precisely by the wicked's continued refusal, not by God's patience running out randomly. The pastoral implication runs in two directions: for the righteous, the armed Judge is a source of confidence; for the unrepentant, a warning that the arrow is nocked."
